1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,850
Now, there's a way I check attitudes and what they mean to job success.

2
00:00:05,120 --> 00:00:14,130
All recommendations for promotions, pay increases, and special privileges are channeled to me by the employee's immediate supervisor.

3
00:00:14,480 --> 00:00:18,850
Almost invariably, it's a Group A person who was recommended.

4
00:00:18,960 --> 00:00:24,610
And again, almost without exception, problems come from the Group B category.

5
00:00:25,360 --> 00:00:33,809
The biggest challenge in my job, he said, is to try and help people move from Group B to Group A. It's not easy,

6
00:00:33,809 --> 00:00:39,330
though, because until a person thinks his job is important and thinks positively about it,

7
00:00:39,440 --> 00:00:40,850
he can't be helped.

8
00:00:41,520 --> 00:00:48,370
This is concrete evidence that you are what you think you are, what your thought power directs you to become.

9
00:00:48,560 --> 00:00:49,730
Think you're weak.

10
00:00:49,840 --> 00:00:51,409
Think you lack what it takes.

11
00:00:51,440 --> 00:00:52,690
Think you will lose.

12
00:00:52,720 --> 00:00:54,610
Think you are second class.

13
00:00:54,800 --> 00:00:58,770
Think this way, and you are doomed to mediocrity.

14
00:00:59,440 --> 00:01:02,289
But think instead, I am important.

15
00:01:02,480 --> 00:01:04,130
I do have what it takes.

16
00:01:04,320 --> 00:01:06,289
I am a first class performer.

17
00:01:06,320 --> 00:01:07,890
My work is important.

18
00:01:08,080 --> 00:01:11,650
Think this way, and you're headed straight to success.

19
00:01:12,400 --> 00:01:17,729
The key to winning what you want lies in thinking positively toward yourself.

20
00:01:18,159 --> 00:01:23,409
The only real basis other people have for judging your abilities is your actions,

21
00:01:23,600 --> 00:01:26,850
and your actions are controlled by your thoughts.

22
00:01:27,280 --> 00:01:29,810
You are what you think you are.

23
00:01:31,280 --> 00:01:39,489
Wear the shoes of a supervisor for a few moments and ask yourself which person you would recommend for a raise or a promotion.

24
00:01:39,489 --> 00:01:41,169
1.

25
00:01:41,520 --> 00:01:47,570
The secretary who, when the executive is out of the office, spends her time reading magazines,

26
00:01:47,679 --> 00:01:55,890
or the secretary who uses such time to do the many little things that help the executive to accomplish more when he returns.

27
00:01:55,890 --> 00:01:57,249
2.

28
00:01:57,520 --> 00:02:01,890
The employee who says, oh, well, I can always get another job.

29
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:05,330
If they don't like the way I do my work, I'll just quit.

30
00:02:05,520 --> 00:02:12,449
Or the employee who views criticism constructively and sincerely tries to do higher quality work.

31
00:02:12,449 --> 00:02:14,050
3.

32
00:02:14,400 --> 00:02:19,169
The salesman who tells a customer, oh, I just do what they tell me to do.

33
00:02:19,280 --> 00:02:21,890
They said come out and see if you need anything.

34
00:02:22,080 --> 00:02:26,610
Or the salesman who says, Mr. Brown, I'm here to help you.

35
00:02:27,840 --> 00:02:28,610
Four.

36
00:02:29,520 --> 00:02:35,250
The foreman who says to an employee, to tell you the truth, I don't like my job much.

37
00:02:35,360 --> 00:02:38,050
Those guys up top give me a pain in the neck.

38
00:02:38,159 --> 00:02:40,689
I don't know what they're talking about half the time.

39
00:02:40,960 --> 00:02:46,610
Or the supervisor who says, you've got to expect some unpleasantness on any job.

40
00:02:46,720 --> 00:02:50,370
But let me assure you, the men in the front office are on the ball.

41
00:02:50,480 --> 00:02:52,209
They'll do right by us.

42
00:02:54,400 --> 00:02:59,169
Isn't it obvious why many people stay at one level all their lives?

43
00:02:59,439 --> 00:03:02,130
Their thinking alone keeps them there.

44
00:03:02,640 --> 00:03:11,570
An advertising executive once told me about his agency's informal training to break in new inexperienced men.